Tectonophysics

Volumes 536–537, 16 April 2012, Pages 25-43

Review Article
Seismic receiver functions and the lithosphere–asthenosphere boundary

Author links open overlay panelRainerKindabXiaohuiYuanaPrakashKumarac
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tecto.2012.03.005Get rights and content

Abstract

The lower boundary of the lithospheric plates has remained as an enigmatic boundary for seismologists, since it is relatively poorly observed by seismic means. There is traditionally a broad consensus that the asthenosphere is observable as a low velocity zone by seismic surface waves. Seismic techniques which use shorter period P-to-S or S-to-P converted body waves are now far enough developed to be successful in observing such a low velocity zone with a higher resolution. The principle of this technique (the so-called receiver function technique) is that a strong teleseismic mother phase (e.g. P, S, PP or SKS) incident from below on any seismic discontinuity beneath a station produces a converted phase (Ps or Sp) which indicates its depth and properties. We discuss details of this technique. A sufficient number of such observations exist already to indicate that the top of the low velocity zone is a globally observable discontinuity and it is sharper than previously thought. An intriguing observation is that in some cratons the new seismic data indicate that the low velocity zone exists already at shallower depths than obtained from surface waves. This confirms earlier results from controlled source observations (Thybo and Perchuc, 1997). We discuss possible interpretations of this shallow low velocity zone in cratonic regions.

Highlights

► Processing steps of the seismic receiver function technique with emphasis on shear wave receiver functions (S-RFs). ► S-RFs - a tool for detection of low velocity zones in the upper mantle, e.g. the lithosphere-asthenosphere boundary (LAB). ► The LAB is observed on a global scale by as a relatively sharp discontinuity with receiver functions. ► A shallow (~ 100km) low velocity zone is found below the North American craton with still unclear interpretation.

1. Introduction

The idea of dividing the uppermost part of the Earth into a mechanically strong lithosphere above a weaker asthenosphere has its origin in the observations of the postglacial rebound observations about hundred years ago (Barrell, 1914, see also Jackson et al., 2008 for a recent review). From about the same time Wegener's “Continental Drift” originates which postulates large horizontal displacements of continents (Wegener, 1912). In his first paper he discussed several possible causes, including sea floor spreading, which was proven half a century later as essential part of the new plate tectonics (see Jacoby, 1981). Gutenberg, 1926, Gutenberg, 1954 proposed a global upper mantle seismic low velocity zone with decreased rigidity and thus permitting continental drift (Jacoby, 1981). In plate tectonics theory the lithosphere is divided laterally into a number of mobile plates. The boundaries of the plates are marked by earthquakes. The lower boundary, e.g., the lithosphere–asthenosphere boundary (LAB), is not marked by seismicity and can only be observed with geophysical means. A number of techniques to determine the LAB have been developed. They do not necessarily lead to identical results (see e. g. Anderson, 1995, Anderson, 2007, Eaton et al., 2009, Jones et al., 2010, Jordan, 1978, Parsons and McKenzie, 1978). One of the greatest challenges in geosciences at the present time lies in identifying the relation between the translating plates and the convecting mantle (Forsyth et al., 2009). Whatever the main contributions to the different properties of the lithosphere and asthenosphere are (temperature, mode of heat transport, viscosity, composition, mineralogy, partial melt, water content, stress, anisotropy, attenuation), the seismic low velocity zone in the upper mantle is probably the observation, which is most frequently equated with the asthenosphere. We consider here possibilities to identify low velocity zones in the uppermost mantle and their transition to the higher velocity lid above with scattered seismic body waves (receiver functions). An especially severe problem in interpreting the asthenosphere as a seismic low velocity zone might be the difference in time scales sampled by seismic waves (seconds to minutes) and postglacial rebound (geological time scales). Although lithosphere and asthenosphere are first order features in dynamic Earth models, they are only weak features in seismic Earth models (Dziewonski and Anderson, 1981, Gutenberg, 1959a, Kennett and Engdahl, 1991). See Kennett (2006) for a discussion of this point.

Why is it difficult to observe the seismological LAB? Historically all global seismic discontinuities have been discovered with wide angle observations. Wide angle means the horizontal part of the travel path is much larger than the vertical part. A low velocity zone is difficult to identify with this technique, because it tends to steepen the seismic wave propagation rather than turn it back to the surface. A classical traveltime curve is constructed and inverted into a velocity–depth model. Gutenberg (1914) applied this technique to global data and proved the existence of the biggest low velocity zone on Earth, which is the outer core. He found defocusing (the core shadow) and focussing effects (caustics) of seismic waves and interpreted them as being caused by a low velocity in the outer core. Using the same technique (observing largely the shadow of the asthenosphere) he introduced a low velocity asthenosphere into his global seismic model (Gutenberg, 1959a, Gutenberg, 1959b). Therefore the upper boundary of the upper mantle low velocity zone is sometimes called the “Gutenberg discontinuity” by seismologists. Now it is more frequently called LAB in a more general, not only in seismological sense. The core–mantle boundary is also sometimes called “Gutenberg discontinuity”. Crustal low velocity zones have also been derived with the same wide angle method (e.g. Müller and Mueller, 1979). Waveform modeling techniques of earthquake records have been used to identify regional low velocity zones in the upper mantle (e.g. Zhao and Helmberger, 1993). Thybo (2006) and Thybo and Perchuc (1997) discussed controlled source observations of an upper mantle low velocity zone (called 8° discontinuity). They suggested that such a zone exists beneath continents and is caused by partial melt. Main sources of their data are recordings of nuclear explosions in the former Soviet Union. High resolution long range controlled source seismic profiles indicated alternating high and low velocity layers in the uppermost mantle (e.g. Kind, 1974). Seismic tomography techniques (surface or body waves) are most frequently used to study the upper mantle (e.g. Kanamori and Press, 1970, Knopoff, 1972, Su et al., 1994). These techniques are sensitive to gradual velocity changes and less sensitive to discontinuities and are therefore less useful for studies of sharp discontinuities. Regional surface wave tomography has a lateral resolution of 300–400 km and a vertical resolution of 30–50 km; teleseismic body wave tomography has a better lateral resolution but poorer vertical resolution (McKenzie and Priestley, 2008, Priestley and Tilmann, 2009). Seismic attenuation or anisotropy may also be used to identify the asthenosphere or the LAB (e.g. Kennett and Abdullah, 2011, Plomerova and Babuska, 2010). In the following we will concentrate on the receiver function technique, especially S receiver functions, which are used intensively since about a decade to study the LAB. Converted body waves are directly sensitive to discontinuities and have due to their short periods and steep incidence angles a higher resolution.

2. Receiver function technique

When a seismic wave is incident on a discontinuity separating two solid materials with different physical parameters, a part of the wave will be reflected and another part will be transmitted. However, there is also a mode conversion from shear (S) waves into compressional (P) waves and vice versa. Therefore, a P wave crossing a discontinuity will generate an S wave (called Ps) which follows the P wave with a slower speed. Similarly, an S wave will produce a P wave (called Sp) which is running ahead with a faster speed. If these wave types are recorded at the surface and their incidence angles and the velocities are known, the depth of the discontinuity where they are generated can be determined from the differential times of the two seismic phases, the mother and daughter phase. The waveforms of both phases carry information about the structure of the discontinuity. Fig. 1 describes the principles of such converted waves for a simple model with two discontinuities (Moho and LAB). It should be mentioned that not only P or S phases may be used in the receiver function technique, also other phases like SKS or PP can be very useful. The processing techniques are very similar for all phases. Since only a small percentage of the incident energy is converted at a discontinuity, it is usually difficult to observe such phases in single seismograms. Summation of many traces from different earthquakes recorded at the same station is therefore used to improve the signal-to-noise ratio. Before summation can be done several processing steps are necessary which will be described next. Summation of records from the same station (receiver) also suppresses effects of the different sources and different parts of the ray path and enhances only receiver site effects. This explains the name “receiver function”, because the seismic discontinuities below the receiver become visible.

Converted seismic waves have been identified and used very early in the history of seismology. In crustal studies converted waves recorded on analogue tapes have been used since the 1950s in a large scale in the former Soviet Union and neighboring countries (Hoffmann et al., 1989, Pomeranceva et al., 1970). A new era in crustal studies started during the 1960s thanks to a growing number of dense seismic experiments using digital data. Phinney (1964) wrote a pioneering paper on “crustal transfer functions” which can be considered a version of the receiver function technique. Burdick and Langston (1977) and Vinnik (1977) started the P receiver function (PRF) technique in its present form which enabled the identification of weak converted phases from the Moho and upper mantle discontinuities. Farra and Vinnik (2000) and Zhou et al. (2000) added incident S waves to the receiver function technique. In the following section we will review basic concepts and processing steps of receiver functions and their capability to detect a low velocity zone in the upper mantle. This review covers both, P and S receiver functions, with emphasis on S receiver functions (SRF). We will show that both methods have advantages and limitations in observing the LAB.

2.1. Separation of P and S waves

Since the converted daughter phase is a different wave type, it is recorded on a different component of the ground motion than the mother phase. The usual vertical, north–south and east–west (ZNE) components of the seismic ground motion should be rotated into a local coordinate system, where each wave type (P, SV and SH) is on its own component. This coordinate system, however, depends on the angle of incidence of the seismic waves, which varies with time. The new system is also frequently called LQT system (see Fig. 2 for S wave incidence). P-to-S converted waves are polarized on the SV (or Q) component, S-to-P converted waves on the P (or L) component; the SH (or T) is free of converted waves in the case of a laterally homogeneous and isotropic Earth. Usually the new coordinate system is determined by diagonalization of the covariance matrix (see e.g. Kind and Vinnik, 1988, Montalbetti and Kanasewich, 1970) which minimizes the SV and SH amplitudes at the P arrival in P receiver functions and the P amplitudes at the S arrival in S receiver functions. In principle this transformation can also be done by variation of the apparent rotation angles (Kumar et al., 2005a, Kumar et al., 2005b, Kumar et al., 2006). Main phase and converted phase have measurable differences in their incident angles. The new coordinate system is oriented on the main phase to avoid leakage of the strong main phase into the weak converted phase. It should be mentioned that free surface effects on the determination of the incidence angle are small (Reading et al., 2003) and usually not considered. In many cases of receiver function application, the ZRT system is used in which R is computed from the theoretical back azimuth (see Fig. 2). The disadvantage of the ZRT system is that significant energy of mother phases (S wave in the case of S-to-P conversion) projects on the component where the weak converted phases (Sp) will be observed. Optimized rotation of the components of ground motion is very important for identifying and enhancing the weak converted signals. The effect of coordinate rotation on waveforms in a vertical plane from the ZR to the LQ components is shown in Fig. 3a, b. The S wave amplitudes on the Z component are moved onto the Q component. The L component contains only the Sp converted waves as precursors to the S wave and the multiple reverberations after the S arrival. The transverse component is omitted as it is less relevant for a homogeneous and isotropic medium.

2.2. Deconvolution

Teleseismic P and S waveforms recorded at three-component seismic stations contain a wealth of information on the earthquake source, the Earth's structure in the vicinity of both source and receiver, and mantle propagation effects. The source and mantle propagation effects can be eliminated by deconvolution, leaving only the response of local crustal and upper mantle structure underneath the station in the receiver functions. Fig. 3c shows the effects of deconvolution on the L and Q components. The S wave train on the Q component (Fig. 3b) is transformed by deconvolution into a relatively sharp spike (Fig. 3c). The resulting L component (Fig. 3c) contains the impulse response of converted and multiply reflected waves. In addition to conventional PRF processing, we reverse the deconvolved L component both in time and amplitude (the red trace in Fig. 3c). We call this trace the SRF, which is directly comparable to the PRF. Most studies so far only analyse the SRF waveform in the positive time window that is dominated by the primary Sp conversions. The multiple reverberations appearing in the negative time window also carry much information on the Earth's structure and therefore may add additional constraints on the discontinuity depth and the seismic velocity (Tseng et al., 2009, Wittlinger et al., 2009). Multiple reverberations are frequently used in PRF (see Zhu and Kanamori, 2000).

In principle deconvolution transforms all recorded L components from different earthquakes into a form which they would have if all sources would have the same waveform and amplitude, for example a spike of the same size. This procedure can only be done approximately. That is why many different versions of this technique exist. Deconvolution can be performed either in frequency or in time domain (e.g. Ammon, 1991). Alternatively, cross-correlation technique is also used (e.g. Helffrich, 2006, Kind and Vinnik, 1988). It should also be mentioned that there is a growing number of RF applications using an iterative pulse stripping time domain deconvolution technique (Ligorria and Ammon, 1999). In the frequency domain, the basic problem is to calculate the Fourier spectral division of the L and Q components (or vertical and radial components). Since the frequency bands of the recordings are constrained, the water-level technique (Clayton and Wiggins, 1976) is used to solve the problem of division instability. In the time domain, the deconvolution is often performed by a Wiener filtering approach (e.g. Berkhaout, 1977, Yuan et al., 1997). The method minimizes the least-square difference between the observed seismogram and the desired delta-like spike function of normalized amplitude. In the case of PRF, an inverse filter is generated from the P waveform on the L component and is convolved with the L and Q components. After deconvolution, all components are normalized to the maximum amplitude of the spike on the L component to preserve the amplitude ratios of the converted phase in percent of the incident mother phase. Because the deconvolution technique in time domain requires for stability reasons a certain length of the source function we choose from experience a window length of about 100 s. The window starts 10 s before the onset of the mother phase (P on the L component or S on the Q component). This long window, however, contains not only the real source function, but also effects of the Earth structure near the source and receiver, for example multiple reflections. Deconvolution considers these signals however as source and eliminates them from the L component. Therefore the L component is rarely used after deconvolution and the Q component is influenced in an undesired and unknown way. Accordingly, the S wave coda contains other phases such as SKS, ScS, SPn etc., which are also treated as source in this technique. Most receiver function applications are ignoring this handicap. These problems are discussed by Bostock, 2004, Bostock, 2007, Baig et al. (2005), Kumar and Bostock (2006) and Kumar et al. (2010). Deconvolution is not the only way to reduce source effects and effects of near source structure. Kumar et al. (2010) show this by summing traces without deconvolution. Influences of the receiver structure are common to all records and will be enhanced by summation, also without deconvolution as first step. Plain summation results in SV component traces which are nearly identical to deconvolved traces while still preserving the P (or L) component (Fig. 4). Kumar et al. (2010) only applied amplitude and sign equalization and summed all traces aligned along the maximum of the P signal. The only disadvantage of the new technique is that more traces are needed to obtain the same signal-to-noise ratio. Fig. 4 shows the systematic errors on the SV component introduced by deconvolution. Although these errors seem small in the theoretical example, they are not predictable in real data. Preserving and using multiples on the P component might provide additional information on P wave velocity in the crust, which is helpful in determining absolute depth of the Moho and absolute average P and S velocities within the crust.

2.3. Moveout correction and summation

After separation of the P and SV wave fields into separate components and source equalization by deconvolution, it is easier to detect the small converted signals. With the large amount of available digital data, weak signals can be enlarged significantly by summation of many records. However, the arrival time of the converted waves is a function of incidence angle, controlled by slowness, which is in turn determined by epicentral distance and focal depth. Slowness is the inverse of the horizontal component of the velocity of a seismic phase; it is inversely proportional to the epicentral distance and it is in seismology frequently used instead of epicentral distance. For example for the S phase, 13 and 9 s/deg slowness corresponds to 59 and 91° epicentral distance, respectively, and for SKS, 6 and 4 s/deg slowness correspond to 89 and 112° epicentral distance. The dependence of the arrival time on the slowness (or distance) is called moveout. The moveout increases with conversion depth, being as large as about 10 s at a source depth of 660 km. The moveout must be corrected before summation of receiver functions. If the seismograms are lined up along the P phase and summed, the Moho signal will also be stacked constructively because the moveout of the Moho conversion is relatively small. The Ps conversion from the discontinuity at 410 km depth, however, will not be stacked constructively in the same summation trace, because this phase travels with a significantly different velocity. In order to sum the conversions from the discontinuity at 410 km depth it would be necessary to align all traces along the expected velocity of this phase. Since all conversions from different discontinuities are traveling with different velocities, it would be necessary to line up the seismic traces separately for each depth where conversion may occur. This is the usual delay and sum technique known from array processing. Vinnik (1977) has applied this technique for observing the upper mantle discontinuities at 410 and 660 km depth.

Another solution is to apply the moveout correction before summation, which is a common procedure in controlled source seismics. A reference velocity–depth model is needed to carry out the moveout correction. Errors introduced by not well known velocity models are relatively small. In this technique the time scale is stretched or compressed in order to parallelise traveltime curves of converted seismic phases from different depths. A fixed reference epicentral distance or slowness (frequently 6.4 s/deg) is used at which the time scale remains unchanged. Moveout correction is called normal moveout correction if a slowness of 0 s/deg (corresponding to vertical incidence) is used as reference slowness. This is usually applied in the reflection seismology. The time scale is compressed at smaller distances than the reference distance, and stretched at larger distances (see Fig. 5). After moveout correction all traces of a certain group of traces may be lined up and summed into a single trace. Such a group of traces could either be all records of one station or all traces having their conversion points within a certain area (common conversion point stacking CCP, in analogy to common depth point stacking CDP in reflection seismics, see Fig. 6). The advantage of the moveout correction and summation technique is that a single summation trace representing a group of traces can easily be compared with another summation trace representing another group of traces. Multiply reflected phases are still destructively superimposed because each type of phases (direct conversions or multiples) needs its own moveout correction. Special moveout corrections may be applied to enhance multiples. Moveout correction and summation is also useful for solving a special problem in SS precursor studies (Heit et al., 2010). Not every precursor of S on the P component is an S-to-P conversion. Surface multiples of the P phase (PP or PPP etc.) could also arrive on the vertical component as precursors of S (Bock, 1994). These phases have, however, very different velocities and can be suppressed in the simple delay and sum technique or in the moveout correction and sum technique.

Fig. 7 shows examples of individual P, S and SKS receiver functions obtained with time domain deconvolution and their summation traces at a station of the Yellowknife array in Canada.

2.4. Migration

Stacked time domain receiver functions are not yet the final goal of the processing. We need to know where in the three dimensional Earth the conversion occurs. Therefore, a final goal is the migration from the time series into a depth model. Depth migration with a known velocity depth model is necessary for this purpose. Migration is also a common practice in controlled source seismics. Due to uneven distribution of stations and events in earthquake seismology a simplified migration approach is often used which employs back projection of reflected or converted phases along the incoming ray path in a 1-D model. The result is an approximate three-dimensional distribution of seismic energy which enables location of seismic discontinuities. Usually, vertical cross sections through such models are displayed. In the case of P receiver functions such images are blurred with multiples from the surface that produce apparent discontinuities. One of the first examples of receiver function depth migration is given by Kosarev et al. (1999). Fig. 8 shows an example of migration of synthetic S receiver functions. A more sophisticated migration development employing Kirchhoff migration or single scatterer approach is presented e.g. by Bostock (2002) and Kind et al. (2002).

The results of the receiver function processing steps described so far indicate the great similarity with steep angle controlled source techniques. Moveout corrections and depth migration are the most important common steps, differences being the frequency content (which determines the resolution) and depth penetration. Steep angle seismics uses frequencies of many Hertz, whereas the teleseismic signals have periods from one to many seconds. Steep angle seismics does not always resolve the Moho (frequently due to insufficient source energy), whereas receiver functions have practically unlimited depth penetration in the upper mantle since the signals are incident from below. Ryberg and Weber (2000) conclude from computations of theoretical seismograms of two dimensional models that a station spacing of a few kilometers is required if structures with similar scale length need to be resolved. This result also implies that the best means for improving the quality of the data is increasing the station density. A station density of a few kilometers is so far reached in very few deployments (e.g. Hansen and Dueker, 2009).

2.5. Receiver function waveforms and thickness of LAB transition

The receiver function processing steps described earlier lead to detection and determination of the depths of discontinuities starting from the base of the sedimentary layers to the upper mantle transition zone in the interior of the Earth, along with their topography. A frequently applied additional step in P receiver functions is the inversion of the waveforms of the receiver function into a one-dimensional velocity–depth model (e.g. Ammon et al., 1990). Problems involved are the non-uniqueness of the inversion and also the assumption that seismic phases which have been generated by a three-dimensional Earth can be approximated by those produced by a one-dimensional model. Even a perfect fit of the observed waveforms with theoretical waveforms cannot overcome the problem of fitting 3-D effects into a 1-D model.

A more realistic scenario seems to be to identify waveforms of conversions from individual discontinuities in P or S receiver functions (e.g. Moho or LAB) and to concentrate in their inversion. Studies of waveforms of S-to-P converted waves from the LAB are still rare. Li et al. (2007) have summed S-to-P converted signals from the LAB recorded at many stations in the western US and inverted the width of the summed signal in terms of thickness of the LAB gradient (Fig. 9, see Fig. 11 for further discussion). They obtained a transition zone of not more than 20 km thickness. However, determinations of the size of the velocity jump and of the thickness of the LAB from summation traces may depend on focusing and defocusing effects of the topography within the region of piercing points and erroneous transformation of topography into the vertical velocity structure. Therefore the summed LAB signal in Fig. 9 was obtained after lining up the individual LAB signals. The 20 km gradient must be considered as an upper limit. With P receiver functions an LAB transition zone of about 11 km was found by Rychert et al., 2005, Rychert et al., 2007 in eastern North America. A similar transition zone was favoured by Rychert and Shearer (2009) from summing many globally distributed P receiver functions.

It should be mentioned that multiples and anisotropy play a less important role in S receiver functions than in P receiver functions because multiples do not interfere with direct conversions and shear wave splitting plays a minor role when SV-to-P converted phases are used. There are a number of papers discussing SH-to-P conversion in the anisotropic case (e.g. Farra et al., 1991, Frederiksen and Bostock, 2000).

3. Detection of the LAB with P and S receiver functions

Both P-to-S and S-to-P converted waves can be generated at the LAB and may be used to detect the LAB by PRF and SRF analyses. For example, Chen (2009), Chen et al. (2008) observed the LAB both in PRF and SRF sections using data from several dense broadband seismic arrays in the North China craton (Fig. 10). They found a wide spread lithospheric thinning beneath the North China craton. A lithospheric thickness of 60–70 km beneath the eastern part of the craton was confirmed by both P and S receiver functions (e.g. Fig. 10a and d). The depth of LAB increases dramatically in the western part, which can be best seen in the SRFs. In this depth range the Ps converted LAB phases appear to be disturbed by the crustal multiples in the PRFs (Fig. 10c and f). The quality of the SRF is usually not as good as that of the PRF. Sometimes the LAB phase cannot be unambiguously picked from the SRF image. In Fig. 10e and f the authors picked the deeper negative phases as the LAB, leaving the strong negative phase immediately beneath the Moho not interpreted.

Many differences between P and S receiver functions must be considered during the processing. SRFs are free of S multiples in front of S and therefore can be very useful to study depth ranges of the mantle lithosphere where PRFs are dominated by crustal multiples. While the P-to-S conversions can be observed over nearly all teleseismic distances, the S-to-P converted waves can only be observed over a limited teleseismic distance range due to the existence of post-critical incidence (approximately 55–85° for S and 85–120° for SKS, see Yuan et al., 2006). S waves usually have lower signal/noise ratio than P waves because they are secondary arrivals interfering with diverse other phases, such as multiple mantle P waves. S waves are characterized by lower frequencies than P waves due to stronger S wave attenuation at higher frequencies in the upper mantle. Therefore, S receiver functions cannot resolve detailed crustal structures, but may be more suited for gradual transition zones, which is presumed for the LAB. S receiver functions sample a broader area than P receiver functions do. At a given depth, piercing points of S-to-P conversions are located farther away from the stations than those of the P-to-S conversions. S receiver functions can be used to expand the sampling area, which is useful for ocean island stations (Li et al., 2004). However, in the case of strong lateral heterogeneities, e.g., the existence of dipping layers, S receiver functions may lose coherence in individual traces and the results may be biased by variable piercing point locations.

Modeling with synthetic receiver functions is very helpful in understanding problems of the processing. In Fig. 11, Fig. 12, Fig. 13 we calculated synthetic receiver functions to demonstrate the abilities of the P and S receiver functions in detecting the LAB. Synthetic seismograms are calculated by the plane wave Haskell matrix propagation method. We used spectral division deconvolution to obtain the synthetic receiver functions.

In contrast to surface waves, receiver functions are sensitive to the sharpness of the LAB transition. In Fig. 11 we show synthetic P and S receiver functions for different values of LAB sharpness. For the models to the left of Fig. 11 with varying transition zone thickness, we calculated PRFs with a Gaussian parameter of 2.7, corresponding to a dominant wave period of ~ 1 s. The crustal interface (C) and the Moho (M) can be clearly seen in the PRFs. However, the LAB converted phase, expected at a time of ~ 17 s, is effectively masked by the strong crustal multiples. SRFs are calculated with three different Gaussian parameters of 0.9, 0.6 and 0.3, corresponding to a dominant wave period of ~ 4 (solid lines), ~ 7 (dashed lines) and ~ 13 s (dotted lines), respectively. In SRFs, the sharp LAB is clearly visible at different periods; although detailed crustal structures are not well resolved (C and M phases are not well separated). As the velocity jump at the LAB becomes more gradational, its expression in the SRFs becomes weaker and broader. For a dominant period of approximately 4–13 s, SRFs appear to be able to resolve the LAB as a 50 km thick gradient zone (green lines). The Sp converted phase is dramatically weaker for a 100 km thick gradient zone (blue lines). Thus S receiver functions have the capability to distinguish between sharp and gradational LAB. The experiment shows that using longer period SRFs (13 s, dotted lines) may amplify the Sp converted phase of a gradual LAB. In an ideal case an LAB with a 100 km gradient might be observed by SRFs with dominant period of 13 s. However SRFs with extremely high signal/noise ratio are needed. We are so far not aware of such observations.

In a series of models shown in Fig. 12, we varied the Moho depth from 20 to 70 km and the LAB is fixed at a depth of 120 km. Gaussian parameters of 2.7 for P and 0.9 for S were are used, so that the dominant wave period of P and S receiver functions are ~ 1 and ~ 4 s, respectively, representing typical dominant period of observed data. In the SRFs (red lines) a positive Moho phase and a negative LAB phase are well separated. In the PRFs (blue lines) the LAB is interfering with multiples for models with Moho depths of 20 and 30 km. With increasing Moho depth the crustal multiples shift to later time, so that the LAB phase becomes visible. Therefore the Moho needs to be deep enough to separate the LAB from the Moho multiples. For a fixed Moho depth only an LAB with a depth shallower than a certain depth can be reliably observed with PRFs. This experiment may partly explain why no deep LAB was reported by a global P receiver function study (Rychert and Shearer, 2009).

PRFs may become more complicated for layered crustal models. A strong shallower crustal interface may complicate the earlier part of the PRF, as shown in Fig. 13. In this case there is no chance for PRF to detect the LAB. The LAB phase is completely masked by internal crustal multiples.

Due to distinct distribution pattern of global earthquakes, the availability of receiver functions varies from place to place on Earth. In Fig. 14 we estimated the potential numbers of receiver function from P, S and SKS waves with earthquakes recorded within a period of five years (2001–2005). The number of PRFs is clearly higher than that of SRFs and SKSRFs. One can expect to obtain many PRFs in the Indian and Pacific oceans as well as in Europe and Asia, but significantly less in South America and Atlantic Ocean. The pattern of SRF distribution is similar to that of the PRF. However, there are even less SRFs in South America. Using receiver functions from SKS waves may help to increase the number of S-to-P converted signals in South America. For designing field experiments, it is certainly very helpful to estimate the rate of useful receiver function which can be expected in a certain region.

4. Some examples

4.1. Iceland

Before discussing the global LAB observations we will consider some regional examples representative for many other regions where with local dense seismic networks tectonic questions have been discussed. The thickness of the elastic lithosphere is determined from Glacial Isostatic Adjustment (GIA) data. Recent modeling of this thickness based on vertical GPS displacement data from stations distributed all over Iceland resulted in a preferred thickness of 40 km within a range of 20 to 70 km (Arnadottir et al., 2009). They are also pointing out that GIA rates are more sensitive to viscosity than to elastic thickness. Considering the large crustal thickness of about 40 km under several regions of Iceland (see e.g. Bjarnason and Schmeling, 2009, Darbyshire et al., 2000, Foulger et al., 2003, Kumar et al., 2007a), this could mean that the shallowest possible LAB would be located within the crust. Kumar et al. (2005a) determined the depth of the LAB in Iceland, Greenland and on Jan Mayen in the north Atlantic using S receiver functions (Fig.15). They obtained a relatively homogeneous lithospheric thickness of about 80 km in most regions of Iceland. Vinnik et al. (2005) obtained a similar thickness also from S receiver functions. Bjarnason and Schmeling (2009) reported LAB depths between 20 and 60 km in most regions of Iceland, except in eastern Iceland, where they found the LAB at a depth of more than 100 km. Their results are obtained from surface wave data, where discontinuities are not directly observed but defined by some gradient in the velocity–depth function. These differences of LAB depth determinations between two seismic methods, receiver functions and surface waves, seem too large to be satisfying. A lithospheric thickness of 70–80 km at a mid ocean ridge and also a plume does not fit very well into the framework of plate tectonics, where a very thin lithosphere is expected. However the S receiver function results seem to be clear and at least not in disagreement with recent glacial isostatic adjustment modeling (Arnadottir et al., 2009). This could mean that the seismic lithosphere under Iceland coincides within error limits with the mechanical lithosphere determined by GIA. Fig.15b shows lithospheric thickness data along the supposed trace of the Iceland plume. The lithosphere shows relatively little variations along this trace. It seems to be somewhat thinner in eastern Greenland and thickens toward western Greenland. No thinning of the lithosphere (like in the case of Hawaii, see Li et al., 2004 and Yuan et al., 2007, or in the case of Gondwanaland (India), see Kumar et al., 2007b) due to the proximity of the plume is observed. The mechanism of plume-lithosphere interaction in Iceland might therefore be feeding of plume materials into the lithosphere thus leading to thickening instead of remelting and thinning as in Hawaii and possibly India. Similar LAB depths have been found by Heit et al. (2007) at Galapagos and Easter Island.

4.2. Central Europe

Geissler et al. (2010) studied the LAB structure in Europe with S receiver functions. They used stations of the permanent European seismic network. The LAB signal is on most stations clearly visible, especially the signals with differential times of less than 14 s or about 125 km LAB depth (Fig. 16). These are mainly stations in the Phanerozoic central Europe. The stations more on the right side of this figure with larger differential times have less clear signals and the stations are mainly located on the East European craton. Some of these stations seem also to have indications of negative signals at times near 10 s. Jones et al. (2010) compared seismic and electromagnetic LAB determinations in Europe and found partly great differences.

4.3. Tibet

Since the beginning of the nineties three large passive seismic experiments have been carried by the international INDEPTH group along a north–south profile across Tibet. A major goal of these experiments has been studies of the fate of the colliding Indian and Asian tectonic plates beneath the Tibetan plateau. A summary of the results, obtained especially from S receiver function studies has been given by Kind and Yuan (2010); see also Fig. 17. The Moho has been observed very well along the entire profile with S and P receiver functions. Clear negative phases, indicating velocity decrease downward, have also been observed with S receiver functions and interpreted as LAB. The subducting Indian LAB was observed reaching nearly to the central part of Tibet at a depth of about 250 km. In the northern part of central Tibet a relatively shallow LAB was observed at a depth near 100 km, which is similar to the LAB depth in central Europe. This structure was interpreted as indication of a separate Tibetan lithosphere. From the north, the Asian lithosphere also seems to subduct and to underthrust the Tibetan lithosphere down to a depth close to 200 km.

The INDEPTH results have shown that S receiver functions are able to image the internal structure of the lithosphere-asthenosphere system, even in complicated collision zones, down to almost 300 km depth with so far unreached resolution.

4.4. Global receiver function observations of the LAB

Rychert and Shearer (2009) have compiled a global map of the LAB using P receiver functions (see also Romanowicz, 2009). They used permanent seismic stations. Because of possible problems with multiples in PRF, a comparison with SRF would be desirable. Rychert and Shearer (2009) find LAB depths of about 70 km beneath oceans, about 80 km in orogenic regions and Phanerozoic platforms, and about 90 km in Precambrian shields. The LAB appeared nowhere deeper than about 120 km in their study. Rychert and Shearer (2009) also find broad agreement of their LAB depth determinations with smooth decreases of surface wave velocities obtained by Nettles and Dziewonski (2008) at the same locations. They also estimated sharp velocity drops of about 3–10% over depths of about 10 km from waveform modeling.

Fischer et al. (2010) have compiled global S receiver function studies with negative signals interpreted as LAB. In Fig. 18 we constructed a preliminary global depth map of the negative signals determined relatively homogeneously by members of our group in Potsdam. Abt et al. (2010, Fig. 19), Ford et al. (2010) and Yuan and Romanowicz (2010) compared in North America and Australia LAB determinations by receiver functions and surface waves. In some parts of both cratons S receiver functions found a shallow (around 100 km) low velocity zone, where according to surface wave studies no LAB is expected. In contrast to that, at larger depths (around 200 km) where traditionally the LAB is thought to be, no low velocity zone was identified at many sites in S receiver functions. As possible cause of this dilemma, Abt et al. (2010), Ford et al. (2010) and Yuan and Romanowicz (2010) suggest that the shallow SRF low velocity zone in cratons is too thin to be detected by surface waves and the deeper surface wave LAB is too gradual to be detected by S receiver functions. The deeper structure is interpreted as broad thermal transition from lithosphere to asthenosphere and the shallower low velocity zone is interpreted as mid-lithospheric structure with a number of possible causes (e.g. anisotropy, composition, partial melt).

4.5. US Array data

The sense of seismic data processing for investigating the Earth's structure is to amplify the weak scattered (reflected and converted) signals. No matter what techniques are used, the quantity and quality of original data are essential. The more data collected, the clearer the Earth can be imaged. It is also helpful to develop comprehensive seismic imaging tools when large amount of data are available. Within the USArray project about 400 seismic stations are installed with 70 km average spacing in the United States. After a period of two years they are moved to the neighboring area thus covering successively the entire territory of the US. All data are openly available through IRIS (http://www.iris.edu/hq/). Up to now the western half of the US is covered to about 94°W. Kumar et al. (2010) have used the available data to construct a map of the top of the upper mantle lows velocity zone in the US using S receiver functions. In Fig. 20 are shown S receiver function data along two profiles across the western US. Only two major signals can be recognized in the upper 300 km, e.g., the Moho and the negative signal underneath, called LAB in Fig. 20. To the west of the Colorado plateau the LAB depth is near 80 km, in agreement with earlier S receiver function data by Li et al. (2007). Beneath the Colorado Plateau the LAB depth reaches nearly 150 km, in agreement with the results from Levander et al. (2011). To the east of Colorado plateau the LAB reaches again shallow depths near about 100 km. There is significant difference in station density between the western and eastern part of the receiver function image. The western part is covered by the dense US Array stations, while only few stations are available in the eastern part. We expect in two years to obtain upper mantle images of similar quality in the eastern part when the US Array is moving over the area.

4.6. Interpretations of negative discontinuities in the uppermost mantle

If there is only one such discontinuity observed, it is often interpreted as mechanical LAB according to the original definition, and in consequence also as shear zone between translating plates and the underlying mantle in terms of plate tectonics. But what are the interpretations if more than one negative discontinuity is observed, perhaps with different seismic (or other) techniques?

Lekic and Romanowicz (2011) and Yuan and Romanowicz (2010) observed with surface waves, for example, a low velocity zone near 100 km depth and anther one near 200 km depth in the central part of the US, as well as in other cratons. They interpret the shallow one as new midlithospheric discontinuity, caused probably by anisotropy and the deeper one as the LAB in the traditional sense. It should be noted that S receiver functions observe only the shallow discontinuity, not the deeper one in the central US (Abt et al., 2010, Kumar et al., 2012).

The model suggested by Mierdel et al. (2007) is in very good agreement with the receiver function observations of a sharp velocity decrease at shallow depths (around 80 km in oceans and around 100 km in continents). They suggest that a sharp decrease of water solubility with depth in aluminous orthopyroxene causes increased melting in the asthenosphere. Their model leads to a sharp upper boundary and a smooth lower boundary of the asthenosphere. In this model the lower part of the asthenosphere changes very gradually over more than hundred kilometers and is therefore difficult to define a bottom of the lithosphere (see Fig. 21a).

Another cause for velocity reductions in the mantle lithosphere was discussed by Karato (2012). This is anelastic relaxation caused by elastically accommodated grain boundary sliding which leads to a large velocity reduction. This model provides a petrological explanation for the seismological observations on the cratonic upper mantle of a large velocity drop in the shallow mantle lithosphere and a small velocity change at larger depth (see Fig. 21b).

Miller and Eaton (2010) explained a shallow low velocity zone in Canada as relict of a Paleo subduction zone. Zhao et al. (2011) observed with S receiver functions in Tibet effects of contemporary continental subduction and stacking of colliding lithospheres down to about 250 km.

5. Conclusions

The P receiver function method has existed for more than thirty years now and has established itself as a robust technique for structural studies of the deeper crust and the upper mantle. The S receiver function technique, however, is only about ten years old and its broader application has started only recently. The great advantage of the S receiver function technique is that ringing due to mainly crustal multiples is clearly separated from the direct conversions. In contrast to the often very complicated P receiver functions, fewer signals are usually visible in good quality S and SKS receiver function data, which are in many regions only the Moho, the LAB and the 410 and 660 discontinuities. More dense station deployments might lead to the detection of more detailed signals from the upper mantle, especially in collision zones. The most significant result of the S receiver function studies so far is the identification of a global distribution of negative signals in the shallow upper mantle. Its interpretation as LAB is widely accepted (in oceans and tectonically active regions), except in some cratons. S receiver functions indicate in the North American craton a strong and shallow (~ 100 km) negative discontinuity but have no evidence for a deep (~ 200 km) negative discontinuity. In contrast, surface wave tomography observes a shallow and a deep negative discontinuity (see Karato, 2012 for a discussion). This dilemma is not yet resolved. Suggested solutions are a so far relatively barely discussed mid-lithospheric low velocity zone (Lekic and Romanowicz, 2011) and/or relicts of paleo subduction zones (Miller and Eaton, 2010). The global existence of shallow LAB signals has also been suggested by Rychert and Shearer (2009) from P receiver function data. For cratons, a shallow low velocity zone has been reported already much earlier from controlled source data (Thybo and Perchuc, 1997). The present state of the discussion of various techniques to study the LAB has recently been summarized by Eaton et al. (2009) and Jones et al. (2010) noting that there may be great differences between the results of different techniques. However recent petrological models suggested by Mierdel et al. (2007) and Karato (2012) seem to be in agreement with the existence of a strong shallow low velocity zone also below cratons.
